<Defs>
  <ThingDef ParentName="ResourceBase">
    <defName>AR_Bronze</defName>
    <label>bronze</label>
    <description>Bronze is an alloy of copper, usually mixed with one part tin and seven parts copper (although other metals can be added with this). It was the first alloy successfully smelted by man on the Old Earth, approximately eight thousand years ago, launching the Bronze Age. Bronze was originally made with copper and arsenic; the discovery of the smelting of tin and copper eliminated the risks of poisoning from the creation of bronze, causing an explosion in its abilities and popularity. Today, bronze is a very hard, heavy alloy and, despite being brittle compared to steel, is an useful (albeit weaker) ingredient in almost any building, weapon, or sculpture imaginable.</description>
    <graphicData>
      <texPath>Items/Stuff/Bronze</texPath>
      <graphicClass>Graphic_StackCount</graphicClass>
      <color>(183,122,61)</color>
    </graphicData>
    <soundInteract>Metal_Drop</soundInteract>
    <soundDrop>Metal_Drop</soundDrop>
    <statBases>
      <MarketValue>1.4</MarketValue>
      <Mass>0.59</Mass>
      <!-- Denser than steel, which is 0.5 -->
      <StuffPower_Armor_Sharp>0.85</StuffPower_Armor_Sharp>
      <StuffPower_Armor_Blunt>0.34</StuffPower_Armor_Blunt>
      <!-- Bronze is brittle -->
      <StuffPower_Armor_Heat>0.57</StuffPower_Armor_Heat>
      <StuffPower_Insulation_Cold>2</StuffPower_Insulation_Cold>
      <StuffPower_Insulation_Heat>2</StuffPower_Insulation_Heat>
      <SharpDamageMultiplier>0.9</SharpDamageMultiplier>
      <BluntDamageMultiplier>1</BluntDamageMultiplier>
      <Flammability>0</Flammability>
    </statBases>
    <stackLimit>100</stackLimit>
    <useHitPoints>false</useHitPoints>
    <healthAffectsPrice>false</healthAffectsPrice>
    <thingCategories>
      <li>ResourcesRaw</li>
    </thingCategories>
    <deepCommonality>4</deepCommonality>
    <deepCountPerPortion>35</deepCountPerPortion>
    <deepLumpSizeRange>20~40</deepLumpSizeRange>
    <stuffProps>
      <categories>
        <li>Metallic</li>
      </categories>
      <appearance>Metal</appearance>
      <commonality>0.8</commonality>
      <!-- Copper and tin are more common -->
      <constructEffect>ConstructMetal</constructEffect>
      <color>(183,122,61)</color>
      <soundImpactBullet>BulletImpact_Metal</soundImpactBullet>
      <soundMeleeHitSharp>MeleeHit_Metal_Sharp</soundMeleeHitSharp>
      <soundMeleeHitBlunt>MeleeHit_Metal_Blunt</soundMeleeHitBlunt>
      <statFactors>
        <MaxHitPoints>0.87</MaxHitPoints>
        <!-- Bronze isn't as strong as steel, whose value is one. -->
        <Beauty>1.1</Beauty>
        <Flammability>0</Flammability>
      </statFactors>
    </stuffProps>
    <terrainAffordanceNeeded>Heavy</terrainAffordanceNeeded>
    <burnableByRecipe>false</burnableByRecipe>
    <smeltable>false</smeltable>
  </ThingDef>
  <ThingDef ParentName="ResourceBase">
    <defName>AR_Copper</defName>
    <label>copper</label>
    <description>Copper is a soft, easily malleable, and highly conductive metal that naturally forms in a brilliant orange color. First used as far back as ten thousand years ago, it is a major component (along with tin or, originally, arsenic) in the production of bronze, a process developed roughly eight thousand years ago. (When mixed with zinc, copper becomes brass.) Copper conducts electricity with peak efficiency and is also an excellent conduit for heat and hot liquids. \n \n The name of the metal comes from one of the most successful Bronze Age societies in Old Earth's classical antiquity: copper was initially mined on the island of Cyprus ("Cyprium", which became "copper") in Roman times.</description>
